00:03:50.640 --> 00:03:53.240
To begin with, as you
can see in the program,

00:03:53.240 --> 00:03:56.410
the Anchiskhati Church Choir is
very important in the revival

00:03:56.410 --> 00:04:01.380
of traditional repertories and also
performance practice in Georgia.

00:04:01.380 --> 00:04:02.680
These two are separate.

00:04:02.680 --> 00:04:08.020 position:56%
For the liturgical tradition, which
was banned through the Soviet period

00:04:08.020 --> 00:04:11.630
from 1921 until 1990,

00:04:11.630 --> 00:04:13.810
the Anchiskhati Choir
has been instrumental

00:04:13.810 --> 00:04:18.310
in recovering this traditional
repertory from archival sources.

00:04:18.310 --> 00:04:20.550
These sources are transcriptions
that were written

00:04:20.550 --> 00:04:24.900
in European notation in the
1880's and 1890's and survived

00:04:24.900 --> 00:04:29.110
in the archives but were rarely
studied and were not published.

00:04:29.110 --> 00:04:34.570
So the Anchiskhati Choir learned of
these archives, transcribed them,

00:04:34.570 --> 00:04:37.140
began singing them in
the Anchiskhati church,

00:04:37.140 --> 00:04:41.330
which is the oldest basilica in
Tbilisi, the capital of Georgia,

00:04:41.330 --> 00:04:45.690
and began publishing chant
books starting in 2000

00:04:45.690 --> 00:04:47.560
as well as CD recordings.

00:04:47.560 --> 00:04:50.310
And from these books and
recordings a whole generation

00:04:50.310 --> 00:04:54.310
of chanters have learned this
ancient medieval repertory

00:04:54.310 --> 00:04:56.890
that was passed through oral
transmission for centuries.

00:04:56.890 --> 00:04:58.440 position:56%
So these gentlemen that will be here

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:02.300
on stage are really considered
the teachers of my generation

00:05:02.300 --> 00:05:04.790
of chanters in Georgia of
which there are hundreds,

00:05:04.790 --> 00:05:06.120
perhaps thousands.

00:05:06.120 --> 00:05:10.430
So it's really an honor and a
privilege to have them here today.

00:05:10.430 --> 00:05:13.920
Now in the Soviet period,
sacred chant was sung,

00:05:13.920 --> 00:05:17.170
but it was mostly a
composed repertory.

00:05:17.170 --> 00:05:22.890
Composers composed simple-style
harmonies to basic melodies

00:05:22.890 --> 00:05:26.270
on the Georgian Orthodox
liturgical texts,

00:05:26.270 --> 00:05:31.650
and they also performed this
music in a European choral style,

00:05:31.650 --> 00:05:36.150
so this was well blended
voices, mixed gender choirs,

00:05:36.150 --> 00:05:40.510
a large vocal range, etc., which
is quite different than the way

00:05:40.510 --> 00:05:46.090
that traditional performance was
actually performed, both folk music

00:05:46.090 --> 00:05:48.900
and liturgical music in
the pre-Soviet period.

00:05:48.900 --> 00:05:52.070
So one thing that the Anchiskhati
Choir has done in addition

00:05:52.070 --> 00:05:54.830
to reviving this traditional
repertory,

00:05:54.830 --> 00:05:58.130
is to go back to the
oldest audio recordings

00:05:58.130 --> 00:06:02.450 position:56%
and to closely examine the ways that
the singers perform their music.

00:06:02.450 --> 00:06:07.380 position:56%
And it turns out that instead of
large choirs, they had small choirs.

00:06:07.380 --> 00:06:10.420
Instead of multiple people
singing each voice part,

00:06:10.420 --> 00:06:14.060
they would have a soloist singing
the top voice and the middle voice

00:06:14.060 --> 00:06:15.940
with perhaps a group
singing the lowest

00:06:15.940 --> 00:06:18.700
of the three-part vocal tradition.

00:06:18.700 --> 00:06:20.570
And the reason that
they had soloists is

00:06:20.570 --> 00:06:23.550
so that the upper two voice
parts could improvise,

00:06:23.550 --> 00:06:26.230
because it's an oral traditional,
and like many oral traditions

00:06:26.230 --> 00:06:29.530
around the world, there's this
element of variation technique

00:06:29.530 --> 00:06:32.010
and improvisation,
which is fundamental

00:06:32.010 --> 00:06:34.590
to the performance of the music.

00:06:34.590 --> 00:06:39.020
And this is where liturgical
music intersects with folk music.

00:06:39.020 --> 00:06:42.100
The folk repertory is
largely improvised.

00:06:42.100 --> 00:06:49.490
Often there are texted
verses contrasted by choruses

00:06:49.490 --> 00:06:53.180
of nonsense syllables, or what we
call vocables, and it's precisely

00:06:53.180 --> 00:06:56.140
on the vocables that you hear
improvisation, and we're going

00:06:56.140 --> 00:06:59.370
to hear those elements
today in the program sung

00:06:59.370 --> 00:07:01.100
by the Anchiskhati Choir.

00:07:01.100 --> 00:07:05.360
So for their traditional
performance practice,

00:07:05.360 --> 00:07:09.010
they have soloists singing
the upper voice parts

00:07:09.010 --> 00:07:10.890
so that they can improvise.

00:07:10.890 --> 00:07:15.000
They sing in more of a natural
voice, a natural timbre, let's say,

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:21.540
that doesn't or tries to avoid any
influences from choral technique

00:07:21.540 --> 00:07:26.250
that we associate with the great
Russian choral schools that came

00:07:26.250 --> 00:07:28.890
into Georgia in the 19th Century--

00:07:28.890 --> 00:07:32.810
what we call generally a Bel canto
style or European choral style.

00:07:32.810 --> 00:07:38.580 position:56%
So what you'll hear today is more of
a bright kind of earthy folk style

00:07:38.580 --> 00:07:42.220
of singing both in the folk
music and the liturgical music,

00:07:42.220 --> 00:07:49.120 position:56%
and this style has been revived from
the old recordings and goes together

00:07:49.120 --> 00:07:51.120
with the traditional repertory.

00:07:51.120 --> 00:07:53.530
So those are just some
teasers for you to listen

00:07:53.530 --> 00:07:56.830
for as we get going
with the performance.

00:07:56.830 --> 00:07:59.350
Okay, so now a word
about where is Georgia.

00:07:59.350 --> 00:08:01.870
I know this is a very educated
audience here in the Library

00:08:01.870 --> 00:08:05.650
of Congress, but still, I
include it just to mention

00:08:05.650 --> 00:08:08.790
that we're not talking
about the state of Georgia.

00:08:08.790 --> 00:08:11.970
Neither are we talking
about Gregorian chant.

00:08:11.970 --> 00:08:15.530
So please don't ask me about
Gregorian chant after the show.

00:08:15.530 --> 00:08:20.440
This is Georgian chant of the
Orthodox rite, and as you can see

00:08:20.440 --> 00:08:23.470
on this little map that I've
included over on the screen

00:08:23.470 --> 00:08:27.480
on the right, Georgia is a
very mountainous country.

00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:31.800
The Caucasus mountain range,
which stretches from the Black Sea

00:08:31.800 --> 00:08:36.060
to the Caspian Sea is the northern
geographical border of Georgia

00:08:36.060 --> 00:08:40.000
and historically separated
Georgia culturally and politically

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:42.460
from the steppes to the north.

00:08:42.460 --> 00:08:45.350
As well, if you look to the south,

00:08:45.350 --> 00:08:49.320
the eastern Anatolian plateau is
also a massive mountain range.

00:08:49.320 --> 00:08:51.600
And these mountains are higher
than the Rockies and Alps,

00:08:51.600 --> 00:08:54.560
so it's a significant
geographical barrier.

00:08:54.560 --> 00:08:57.840
And within these mountains there
are many, many different cultures.

00:08:57.840 --> 00:09:02.500
Just in Dagestan alone I believe
there are 29 mutually distinct

00:09:02.500 --> 00:09:03.970
languages and culture groups.

00:09:03.970 --> 00:09:07.150
The Persians called this area
the mountain of languages,

00:09:07.150 --> 00:09:11.880
and within Georgia there are four
languages that are closely related

00:09:11.880 --> 00:09:13.440
but mutually unintelligible.

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:17.170
Think of French to
Italian to Spanish.

00:09:17.170 --> 00:09:19.150
So there are four languages
like that

00:09:19.150 --> 00:09:21.140
in a group called the
Kartvelian language group,

00:09:21.140 --> 00:09:22.920
and these are not Indo-European,

00:09:22.920 --> 00:09:26.240
and they have no analogue
elsewhere in the world.

00:09:26.240 --> 00:09:28.280
Georgian culture goes
back 5000 years.

00:09:28.280 --> 00:09:30.420
They say that wine was
invented in Georgia,

00:09:30.420 --> 00:09:35.310
and indeed they found grape pips
and buried amphoras in Georgia

00:09:35.310 --> 00:09:39.040
and in the Armenian region,
which is a source of great pride

00:09:39.040 --> 00:09:42.040 position:56%
for all Georgians, and in fact
today it's still a living tradition.

00:09:42.040 --> 00:09:46.300
Many villagers, many people take
pride in making their own wine

00:09:46.300 --> 00:09:48.640
in their own buried
amphoras in their backyards.

00:09:48.640 --> 00:09:52.330
So there's a great viniculture
tradition, which goes hand in hand

00:09:52.330 --> 00:09:56.980
with singing as we all know,
so that's why I mentioned it.

00:09:56.980 --> 00:09:59.920
A political map from
the mid-20th Century.

00:09:59.920 --> 00:10:02.920 position:56%
You can see that Georgia is bordered
to the south by Turkey, Armenia

00:10:02.920 --> 00:10:07.700
and Azerbaijan, to the north by the
various North Caucasian Republics

00:10:07.700 --> 00:10:12.150
such as Chechnya, Ingushetia,
Kabardino, Balkaria

00:10:12.150 --> 00:10:18.260
and various other states that are
now part of the Russian federation.

00:10:18.260 --> 00:10:23.900
When we talk about music, we talk
about 12 regions within Georgia

00:10:23.900 --> 00:10:28.590
that have their own distinct
dialects, cuisine, clothing,

00:10:28.590 --> 00:10:32.910
and musical styles, and these
musical styles have something

00:10:32.910 --> 00:10:36.430
in common, which is that they
are mostly all three-part harmony

00:10:36.430 --> 00:10:38.220
folk-singing traditions.

00:10:38.220 --> 00:10:41.240
There are folk instruments, but
they generally accompany a singing

00:10:41.240 --> 00:10:44.940
tradition, which is
almost always polyphonic,

00:10:44.940 --> 00:10:48.790
and that distinguishes Georgian
folk music from other music systems

00:10:48.790 --> 00:10:51.860
in the area, which are
mostly monophonic; that is,

00:10:51.860 --> 00:10:56.130
highly ornamented solo lines that
are played on instruments or sung

00:10:56.130 --> 00:10:59.110
by vocalists, but the
Georgian music is polyphonic,

00:10:59.110 --> 00:11:00.510
so this is a big difference.

00:11:00.510 --> 00:11:03.980
Now within Georgia we have as
I mentioned the 12 regions,

00:11:03.980 --> 00:11:07.600
and I've designed the program
today such that we'll be starting

00:11:07.600 --> 00:11:12.640
in East Georgia, and we'll be
hearing a chant or two, two chants,

00:11:12.640 --> 00:11:15.950
and then a folk song from East
Georgia, and what I'd ask you

00:11:15.950 --> 00:11:21.350
to listen to are the ways in which
the harmony of the folk music

00:11:21.350 --> 00:11:24.060
and chant resemble one
another in this region.

00:11:24.060 --> 00:11:26.930
And then as we move into
central Georgia and then finally

00:11:26.930 --> 00:11:29.700
to West Georgia you'll hear how
the harmony of both the folk

00:11:29.700 --> 00:11:32.320
and sacred music influence
one another.

00:11:32.320 --> 00:11:37.500 position:56%
So it's most scholars opinion that
Greek monophonic chant melodies came

00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:40.250
into Georgia maybe as
early as the fourth century

00:11:40.250 --> 00:11:42.690
when Georgia converted
to Christianity,

00:11:42.690 --> 00:11:45.910
but it's through a process
of vernacularization

00:11:45.910 --> 00:11:48.570
of both the biblical
text and the way

00:11:48.570 --> 00:11:52.760
that those biblical texts were
performed in the ritual services

00:11:52.760 --> 00:11:56.750
that probably very early on these
monophonic melodies imported

00:11:56.750 --> 00:12:02.210
from Jerusalem and Antioch would
have been sung in polyphony.

00:12:02.210 --> 00:12:04.550
So the dating of when
this polyphony,

00:12:04.550 --> 00:12:08.430
or polyphonic vernacularization,
occurred is under debate.

00:12:08.430 --> 00:12:11.880 position:56%
Some scholars say it was as early as
the fourth, fifth, sixth centuries.

00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:14.090
Other scholars say there's no
evidence, maybe it happened

00:12:14.090 --> 00:12:18.310
in the middle ages, the 10th, 11th
centuries, but you get the idea.

00:12:18.310 --> 00:12:24.710
This is a very old, polyphonic
performance of liturgical melodies,

00:12:24.710 --> 00:12:30.060
which is unique to this
eastern segment of Christianity.

00:12:30.060 --> 00:12:33.790
Of course Russian polyphony
exists but it occurs much later.

