00:29:54.200 --> 00:29:55.500
Before we move to West Georgia,

00:29:55.500 --> 00:29:57.380
I'll just say a quick
note about the instrument.

00:29:57.380 --> 00:30:01.410
This is the chonguri, a four-string
lute that we find in West Georgia,

00:30:01.410 --> 00:30:04.380
all the West Georgian regions,
that has one fixed string.

00:30:04.380 --> 00:30:06.150
So it's like a banjo.

00:30:06.150 --> 00:30:10.360
The actual strumming is on three
strings, but it's unfretted,

00:30:10.360 --> 00:30:11.870
which allows the instrument

00:30:11.870 --> 00:30:15.840
to accommodate the unique
Georgian intonation system,

00:30:15.840 --> 00:30:20.890
which we'll be talking about a
little bit later in the Q and A.

00:30:20.890 --> 00:30:24.450
So now as we move to far Western
Georgia, these are the hills

00:30:24.450 --> 00:30:28.130
of Guria and Achara on
the Black Sea coast.

00:30:28.130 --> 00:30:32.640
This area of the country was
sometimes under Ottoman control

00:30:32.640 --> 00:30:36.990
for the last 400 years,
sometimes under Georgian control.

00:30:36.990 --> 00:30:41.410
First we'll hear the Kriste
Aghdga, Christ is Risen.

00:30:41.410 --> 00:30:44.880
We'll hear three versions
as recorded in 1966,

00:30:44.880 --> 00:30:47.930
by the last master chanter,
Artem Erkomaishvili.

00:30:47.930 --> 00:30:51.510
So you'll hear the ways that he
plays with the model melodies,

00:30:51.510 --> 00:30:56.220
the ways that he improvises
and varies his own melody.

00:30:56.220 --> 00:30:59.240
And what I will say that
distinguishes this harmony

00:30:59.240 --> 00:31:01.980
from the harmony that we've
been listening to so far is

00:31:01.980 --> 00:31:06.160
that they love the dissonances in
the Shemokmedi Monastery region.

00:31:06.160 --> 00:31:11.260 position:56%
So you'll hear a lot of close second
intervals in the upper voices,

00:31:11.260 --> 00:31:14.700
and he also loves wide
open fifth chords,

00:31:14.700 --> 00:31:17.060
so the upper voices will
have an interval of a fifth

00:31:17.060 --> 00:31:20.070
with another fifth below
it, what we call a ninth.

00:31:20.070 --> 00:31:23.050
So you'll hear a lot of
this fifth-ninth harmony,

00:31:23.050 --> 00:31:27.240
sometimes in parallel,
which is similar to tenth

00:31:27.240 --> 00:31:30.890
and eleventh century polyphony
as it started in Europe,

00:31:30.890 --> 00:31:35.210
but it quickly developed away, and
as we know from music theory 101,

00:31:35.210 --> 00:31:38.580
no parallel fifths or octaves
are allowed in western music.

00:31:38.580 --> 00:31:40.000
Well not in Georgia.

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:44.010
In Georgia they kept the parallel
fifths, octaves, and even ninths.

00:31:44.010 --> 00:31:47.480
So now we're in far Western
Georgia, and after this,

00:31:47.480 --> 00:31:51.300
