00:54:35.060 --> 00:54:38.660
And finally, before we transition
to a Question and Answer session,

00:54:38.660 --> 00:54:40.830
I just wanted to speak a
little bit more briefly

00:54:40.830 --> 00:54:43.180
about this intonation
system, this tuning system,

00:54:43.180 --> 00:54:45.290
which I think is really
interesting and something

00:54:45.290 --> 00:54:47.070
that Georgian music has to offer.

00:54:47.070 --> 00:54:50.110
And since we have these experts
here, we might as well mention it.

00:54:50.110 --> 00:54:51.410
There are various theories.

00:54:51.410 --> 00:54:55.320
One is that there's an
octave species as you see

00:54:55.320 --> 00:54:59.760
on this little graphic, where
certain pitches are tuned higher

00:54:59.760 --> 00:55:02.660
or lower, and there's conjunct
and disjunct tetra chords.

00:55:02.660 --> 00:55:04.960
Various theories map the
ancient Greek music theory

00:55:04.960 --> 00:55:06.890
onto the Georgian scale.

00:55:06.890 --> 00:55:11.430
Levan and Zaza's theory is
that the octave is divided

00:55:11.430 --> 00:55:17.010
by equal heptatonic steps, so 7
steps in the scale instead of 12.

00:55:17.010 --> 00:55:19.830
You can see from this little
graphic that I made up.

00:55:19.830 --> 00:55:22.560
On the left you have
equal tempered tuning.

00:55:22.560 --> 00:55:26.310
The darker shaded gray areas are
half steps, what we were familiar

00:55:26.310 --> 00:55:31.330
with from guitar tuning, piano
tuning, etc. These are measured

00:55:31.330 --> 00:55:32.630
by what we call cents [phonetic].

00:55:32.630 --> 00:55:35.470
So a half step would be 100 cents,
as you see here dark shaded,

00:55:35.470 --> 00:55:39.160
and a whole step would be
200 cents, or two half steps.

00:55:39.160 --> 00:55:44.090
Meanwhile Georgian intervals
are more like 160 or 170 cents,

00:55:44.090 --> 00:55:47.870
so they're neither half steps nor
whole steps, and we can hear this

00:55:47.870 --> 00:55:51.170
in all of the recordings that
we have from the master singers

00:55:51.170 --> 00:55:53.930
and master chanters,
especially Artem Erkomaishvili,

00:55:53.930 --> 00:55:55.470
that we've heard from today.

00:55:55.470 --> 00:55:58.100
So, I'm sorry the graphic
is a little bit small,

00:55:58.100 --> 00:56:00.710
but if you see the darkest line,

00:56:00.710 --> 00:56:03.850
horizontal lines, the
octaves are equal.

00:56:03.850 --> 00:56:07.880
The fifth below the high octave,
it's about equal in the Georgian

00:56:07.880 --> 00:56:10.240
and the tempered tuning,
but the pitches

00:56:10.240 --> 00:56:13.950
that really differ are
the third and the sixth,

00:56:13.950 --> 00:56:17.070
so this sort of comes close to
what we call just intonation

00:56:17.070 --> 00:56:19.090
or baroque intonation in Europe,

00:56:19.090 --> 00:56:22.080
where you have neutral
thirds and neutral sixths.

00:56:22.080 --> 00:56:26.660 position:56%
I'm not talking microtones, not
tiny tones, these are actually wider

00:56:26.660 --> 00:56:30.860
than a half step, and what we get
are these kind of neutral chords

00:56:30.860 --> 00:56:33.800
that neither feel minor nor major.

