01:15:56.460 --> 01:16:01.400
of music from Svaneti?

01:16:02.720 --> 01:16:05.800
&gt;&gt; John A. Graham: Musical
features of music from Svaneti.

01:16:05.800 --> 01:16:11.510
&gt;&gt; Audience member: Yes,
anything to inform the public.

01:16:11.510 --> 01:16:45.250
[ Foreign Language ]

01:16:45.250 --> 01:16:48.390
&gt;&gt; John A. Graham: So Dato says
that the region of Svaneti is one

01:16:48.390 --> 01:16:50.900
of the mountain regions
in Western Georgia

01:16:50.900 --> 01:16:57.010
where folklore was most protected,
so we still have singers there

01:16:57.010 --> 01:16:59.440
who sing in the original
intonation style

01:16:59.440 --> 01:17:02.510
who haven't been influenced
by other musical styles.

01:17:02.510 --> 01:17:09.040
[ Foreign Language ]

01:17:09.040 --> 01:17:13.230
And this music culture at Svaneti
is alive in all generations.

01:17:13.230 --> 01:17:15.410
So the grandparents will sing,

01:17:15.410 --> 01:17:18.510
and the grandchildren
will sing with them.

01:17:18.510 --> 01:17:35.180
[ Foreign Language ]

01:17:35.180 --> 01:17:38.760
And they have a particular style
of singing that's different

01:17:38.760 --> 01:17:41.490
from all the other
regional styles as I said,

01:17:41.490 --> 01:17:44.510
and I should mention they
also speak a unique language.

01:17:44.510 --> 01:17:47.240
[ Inaudible Comment ]

01:17:47.240 --> 01:17:52.690 position:56%
Was your question about the harmony,
