01:17:52.690 --> 01:17:53.990
[laughter]

01:17:53.990 --> 01:17:57.280
&gt;&gt; Audience member:
[Inaudible] anything about Racha?

01:17:57.280 --> 01:17:59.080
&gt;&gt; John A. Graham: And about Racha?

01:17:59.080 --> 01:18:19.070
[ Foreign Language ]

01:18:19.070 --> 01:18:21.830
So Racha is a neighboring
mountain region to Svaneti,

01:18:21.830 --> 01:18:24.380
and these places are
fantastic to visit by the way.

01:18:24.380 --> 01:18:28.370
If you can ever come
to Georgia, please.

01:18:28.370 --> 01:18:33.290
So Racha, Dato says that Rachan
folklore is similar to Svan

01:18:33.290 --> 01:18:35.720
in some ways, being a
neighbor mountain region,

01:18:35.720 --> 01:18:37.930
but interestingly it also,

01:18:37.930 --> 01:18:42.120
Rachan harmony also resembles
Eastern Georgian harmony,

01:18:42.120 --> 01:18:46.650
which is very curious since it's a
Western Georgian mountain region,

01:18:46.650 --> 01:18:50.360
possibly suggesting some sort
of cultural contact or some type

01:18:50.360 --> 01:18:53.510
of movement of a population
at some point.

01:18:53.510 --> 01:19:18.040
[ Foreign Language ]

01:19:18.040 --> 01:19:23.110
So the choice is a Svanetian
para-liturgical hymn called Lile.

01:19:23.110 --> 01:19:28.130
Lile was one of the gods in
the pantheon of [inaudible]

01:19:28.130 --> 01:19:32.510
in Svaneti before Christianity
arrived.

