01:21:09.820 --> 01:21:12.590
&gt;&gt; Audience member: What are some
of the characteristics of the music

01:21:12.590 --> 01:21:17.380
that typically accompanies
dance traditions in Georgia?

01:21:19.510 --> 01:21:27.050
[ Foreign Language ]

01:21:27.050 --> 01:21:29.530
&gt;&gt; John A. Graham: As
everywhere, rhythm.

01:21:29.530 --> 01:21:33.140
And also the instruments that
they play often accompany dance,

01:21:33.140 --> 01:21:35.790
especially the bagpipe.

01:21:35.790 --> 01:21:38.630
And they also have a
doli, the two-headed drum.

01:21:38.630 --> 01:21:40.430
What else?

01:21:40.430 --> 01:21:45.470
[ Foreign Language ]

01:21:45.470 --> 01:21:48.130
Also the-- whenever
they start clapping,

01:21:48.130 --> 01:21:51.370
that's usually an indication
that the young dancers will come

01:21:51.370 --> 01:21:53.600
and dance in front of the choir.

01:21:53.600 --> 01:21:57.960
And I'll mention that there's
a whole genre of songs,

01:21:57.960 --> 01:22:01.200
especially from the mountains,
called rounds dance songs,

01:22:01.200 --> 01:22:06.570
which were performed by the whole
family or the whole village,

01:22:06.570 --> 01:22:09.720
and they could last for many,
many, many minutes usually

01:22:09.720 --> 01:22:11.380
in an antiphonal type of setup

01:22:11.380 --> 01:22:13.890
where there are two choirs
responding, one to another.

01:22:13.890 --> 01:22:18.930 position:56%
One has a verse, the other responds,
and they continue a round dance.

01:22:18.930 --> 01:22:22.420
And the footwork is
often quite difficult.

01:22:22.420 --> 01:22:26.460
It looks simple, but it's on a
different rhythm than the singing.

01:22:26.460 --> 01:22:28.110
I know because I taught
my choir round dances,

01:22:28.110 --> 01:22:32.510
and it was always very difficult.

01:22:32.510 --> 01:23:01.050
[ Foreign Language ]

01:23:01.050 --> 01:23:04.100
So Dato says that there are
a few famous dance companies

01:23:04.100 --> 01:23:12.850
that have been big exports
from Georgia culturally,

01:23:12.850 --> 01:23:16.780
so [foreign language] large
dance companies, and this is sort

01:23:16.780 --> 01:23:20.780
of a professionalized version
of traditional dance steps,

01:23:20.780 --> 01:23:25.570
but he says the more folk-style
authentic dance still exists,

01:23:25.570 --> 01:23:29.070
especially in mountain
cultures like Svaneti.

01:23:29.070 --> 01:23:31.130
[ Foreign Language ]

01:23:31.130 --> 01:23:35.180
But we can't demonstrate that.

01:23:38.090 --> 01:23:40.260
[laughter] Did you have--

01:23:40.260 --> 01:23:45.660
&gt;&gt; Audience member: Are the neumes
in any way related to punctuation?

01:23:45.660 --> 01:23:46.960
&gt;&gt; John A. Graham:
So the question is:

01:23:46.960 --> 01:23:49.510
are neumes related to punctuation?

01:23:49.510 --> 01:24:18.100
[ Foreign Language ]

01:24:18.100 --> 01:24:23.230
So phrases in the tenth century
hymnographic text were divided

01:24:23.230 --> 01:24:26.510
with punctuation.

01:24:26.510 --> 01:24:42.180
[ Foreign Language ]

01:24:42.180 --> 01:24:46.980
The other symbols in the Georgia
neume system are not necessarily

01:24:46.980 --> 01:24:49.300
punctuation specific but have more

01:24:49.300 --> 01:24:52.220
to do what we think
with melodic movement.

01:24:52.220 --> 01:24:56.680
So there's various symbols, and
they'll be specifically placed

01:24:56.680 --> 01:24:59.350
above the syllable on which
the melody needs to move

01:24:59.350 --> 01:25:00.650
in one direction or another.

01:25:00.650 --> 01:25:02.110
[ Foreign Language ]

01:25:02.110 --> 01:25:03.740
Placed above, or below, the text.

01:25:03.740 --> 01:25:07.090
That's an important element, which
distinguishes the Georgian system

01:25:07.090 --> 01:25:10.510
from any other neume systems.

01:25:10.510 --> 01:25:13.060
[ Foreign Language ]

01:25:13.060 --> 01:25:17.190
Eleven symbols in the
10th century system.

01:25:18.510 --> 01:25:28.080
[ Foreign Language ]

01:25:28.080 --> 01:25:30.020
Zaza also wants to
mention that in addition

01:25:30.020 --> 01:25:33.620
to the tenth century neume system
we have later neume systems

01:25:33.620 --> 01:25:35.680
that have some resemblance
but are not the same.

01:25:35.680 --> 01:25:40.250
These occur in 18th, 19th,
and 20th century sources.

01:25:41.830 --> 01:25:45.670
