01:25:55.350 --> 01:25:58.580
&gt;&gt; Audience member: I noticed
they ended in unison, their songs.

01:25:58.580 --> 01:26:08.120
Is there a reason why the secular
and the sacred are in unison?

01:26:10.510 --> 01:26:17.080
[ Foreign Language ]

01:26:17.080 --> 01:26:20.210
&gt;&gt; John A. Graham: So the
question is about unison finals

01:26:20.210 --> 01:26:24.510
for both folk songs
and liturgical chant.

01:26:24.510 --> 01:26:31.040
[ Foreign Language ]

01:26:31.040 --> 01:26:35.510 position:56%
So Dato says most phrases end either
with an open fifth or with unison.

01:26:35.510 --> 01:26:39.040
[ Foreign Language ]

01:26:39.040 --> 01:26:40.930
It's very rare that a phrase
would end, for example,

01:26:40.930 --> 01:26:43.510
in another interval like an octave.

01:26:43.510 --> 01:27:00.040
[ Foreign Language ]

01:27:00.040 --> 01:27:04.090 position:56%
So the liturgical system, Dato says,
has more rules, and one of the rules

01:27:04.090 --> 01:27:06.560
that we observe in the
transcription record is

01:27:06.560 --> 01:27:08.280
that the chants end in unison.

01:27:08.280 --> 01:27:15.510 position:56%
